const content = "<section class=\"tcs-section tcs-section--deep-navy\">\n  <div class=\"tcs-container\">\n\n      <span class=\"tcs-label-pill\">Canada \u2022 Market Intelligence</span>\n      <h1 class=\"tcs-heading-xl\">Canada Online Casino Market Report 2025</h1>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"tcs-review-block\" style=\"margin-top:24px; padding:22px 24px; border-radius:14px; border:1px solid #3b348f; background:rgba(10,9,40,0.85);\">\n  <span class=\"tcs-label-pill\">TL;DR \u2022 2025 Snapshot</span>\n  <h3 style=\"margin-top:10px;\">Canada Online Casino Market \u2014 Key Insights</h3>\n\n  <ul style=\"margin-top:12px;\">\n\n    <li><strong>Canada remains one of the world\u2019s most active iGaming markets:</strong>  \n      National participation rates exceed global averages, with Ontario operating a fully regulated market and the rest of Canada continuing in a stable grey-market environment.\n    </li>\n\n    <li><strong>Ontario regulation is reshaping the industry:</strong>  \n      AGCO/iGO enforcement has tightened advertising, bonus structures and data requirements.  \n      Meanwhile, non-Ontario players continue accessing larger offshore bonuses with lighter restrictions.\n    </li>\n\n    <li><strong>Interac dominates payments nationwide:</strong>  \n      Interac e-Transfer remains Canada\u2019s #1 deposit and withdrawal method, with top operators completing payouts in 30 minutes to 6 hours.  \n      Processor-level friction is increasing, pushing casinos to adopt more automated rails.\n    </li>\n\n    <li><strong>Crypto use is rising outside Ontario:</strong>  \n      USDT (TRC20) and BTC continue gaining popularity due to payout reliability, especially during evening and weekend banking windows when Interac delays are common.\n    </li>\n\n    <li><strong>Bonus trends are shifting toward fairness:</strong>  \n      Operators are reducing wagering ranges, publishing more transparent RTP data, and eliminating predatory max-cashout conditions.  \n      Ontario bonuses are smaller but regulated; non-Ontario bonuses are larger but vary in quality.\n    </li>\n\n    <li><strong>Cloned Canadian casino domains are increasing:</strong>  \n      Scam sites targeting Interac and crypto deposits are up noticeably in 2024\u20132025, making licence verification and domain stability critical for player safety.\n    </li>\n\n    <li><strong>Mobile-first behaviour dominates the Canadian market:</strong>  \n      72\u201378% of sessions occur on mobile devices, making mobile UX, banking flow and slot performance major factors in our TCS Score outcomes.\n    </li>\n\n  </ul>\n\n  <p style=\"margin-top:14px; opacity:0.88;\">\n    Quick takeaway: Canada\u2019s market is maturing quickly \u2014 with Ontario becoming tightly regulated and the rest of Canada relying on trusted offshore brands.  \n    For players, the biggest factors in 2025 are payout reliability, Interac vs. crypto availability, transparent bonus terms, and choosing operators that pass monthly TCS safety audits.\n  </p>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<section class=\"tcs-section tcs-section--deep-navy\" style=\"margin-top:48px;\">\n  <div class=\"tcs-container\">\n    <div class=\"tcs-review-block\">\n\n      <span class=\"tcs-label-pill\">Canada \u2022 Market Intelligence</span>\n      <h1 class=\"tcs-heading-xl\">Canada Online Casino Market Report 2025</h1>\n\n      <p class=\"tcs-text-lead\" style=\"margin-top:16px;\">\n        The Canadian online casino market entering 2025 is defined by a unique regulatory split,\n        a maturing consumer base, rapid payment-method evolution, and increasing differentiation\n        between Ontario\u2019s regulated ecosystem and the grey-market environment serving the rest of Canada.\n        This report combines TCS Score data, operator audits, payment-flow testing, and player-behaviour\n        modelling to map the real, measurable conditions shaping Canada\u2019s digital gambling landscape.\n        Insights reflect observations from Q1\u2013Q4 2024 and forward-looking signals from 2025 regulator,\n        operator and consumer trends.\n      </p>\n\n      <!-- SECTION: REGULATORY LANDSCAPE -->\n      <h2 style=\"margin-top:36px;\">1. Canada\u2019s Two-Track Regulatory Structure</h2>\n\n      <p>\n        Since April 2022, Canada has operated the only split-market regulatory model in the Western world:\n        a provincially regulated, open-license market in Ontario, and a parallel grey-market landscape across\n        the remaining provinces and territories. Operators, payment processors and affiliates must navigate\n        two completely different sets of rules, player expectations and product constraints.\n      </p>\n\n      <h3>1.1 Ontario (AGCO / iGO) \u2014 North America\u2019s Strictest Commercial Model</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        Ontario remains the only fully regulated, open commercial online casino market in Canada.  \n        Operators must obtain separate approvals from:\n      </p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li><strong>AGCO (Alcohol and Gaming Commission of Ontario):</strong> oversight, compliance, integrity, risk controls.</li>\n        <li><strong>iGO (iGaming Ontario):</strong> contractual agreements and revenue-share structure.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p>\n        Ontario\u2019s regulatory framework emphasises transparency, responsible gambling, controlled advertising,\n        anti-money laundering, and player-fund security. It also enforces strict RTP publication standards,\n        requires segregated funds, and mandates audits of RNG and game fairness.\n      </p>\n\n      <p><strong>Key 2024\u20132025 Ontario trends:</strong></p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li>Reduced promotional freedom due to ongoing marketing restrictions.</li>\n        <li>Strong push toward <strong>deposit limits</strong>, behavioural analytics and safer-gambling interventions.</li>\n        <li>More than 70 licensed operators, resulting in a competitive but predictable marketplace.</li>\n        <li>High trust from Ontario players due to regulatory clarity.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <h3>1.2 The Rest of Canada \u2014 A Mature, Competitive Grey Market</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        Outside Ontario, Canada operates under federal and provincial frameworks that do not license private\n        operators directly. This creates a well-established grey-market environment where offshore casinos\n        legally serve players, provided they meet international licensing and KYC standards.\n      </p>\n\n      <p>\n        Provinces such as British Columbia, Quebec and Alberta run their own crown-corporation gaming portals,\n        but private offshore operators dominate real-money casino traffic due to broader game availability,\n        stronger bonuses, higher RTP transparency and diverse payment options.\n      </p>\n\n      <p><strong>Non-Ontario regulatory signals shaping 2025:</strong></p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li>Growing expectation of a future multi-province licensing model (Quebec is the leading candidate).</li>\n        <li>Increasing pressure on operators to maintain compliance around AML and crypto deposits.</li>\n        <li>More scrutiny around unverified licensing claims and cloned-brands targeting Canadian GEOs.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <h3>1.3 Kahnaw\u00e0ke\u2019s Continued Influence</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        The <strong>Kahnaw\u00e0ke Gaming Commission (KGC)</strong> remains a respected regulatory body for operators\n        serving non-Ontario Canadian players. Stability, transparency and a strong dispute-resolution track\n        record keep Kahnaw\u00e0ke-licensed brands among the most trusted in the grey market.\n      </p>\n\n      <p><strong>2025 updates:</strong> increased on-site audits, improved AML standards, and stronger data-retention rules.</p>\n\n      <!-- SECTION: PAYMENT SYSTEMS -->\n      <h2 style=\"margin-top:42px;\">2. Canadian Payment System Evolution (2024\u20132025)</h2>\n\n      <p>\n        Canada\u2019s payment infrastructure continues to evolve faster than the online casino regulatory landscape.\n        TCS Score banking tests conducted throughout 2024\u20132025 reveal a major shift in preferred deposit and\n        withdrawal methods, as well as changing risk controls from payment intermediaries.\n      </p>\n\n      <h3>2.1 Interac Dominance \u2014 But Not Without Changes</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        <strong>Interac e-Transfer</strong> remains the national standard for deposits and withdrawals across the\n        grey market. Operators typically use intermediary processors to enable automated Interac flows.\n      </p>\n\n      <p><strong>Key observations:</strong></p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li>Interac success rates remain high (92\u201396% across TCS tests).</li>\n        <li>Withdrawal times have improved \u2014 many operators now process within 1\u20134 hours.</li>\n        <li>Increased velocity limits and risk scoring affect high-volume players.</li>\n        <li>Processors are tightening anti-fraud triggers in line with banking expectations.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <h3>2.2 Decline of Legacy Wallets (MuchBetter, iDebit, Instadebit)</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        Previously dominant e-wallets have seen steep declines in support and reliability:\n      </p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li><strong>MuchBetter:</strong> service disruptions in 2023\u20132024 drastically reduced adoption.</li>\n        <li><strong>iDebit / Instadebit:</strong> minimal growth, slower withdrawals, reduced operator support.</li>\n        <li><strong>ecoPayz:</strong> maintains a small but stable presence with high-roller usage.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p>\n        The shift away from legacy wallets has streamlined the Canadian banking profile \u2014 with Interac, crypto, and direct\n        card payments now holding the vast majority share of transactions.\n      </p>\n\n      <h3>2.3 Rapid Growth in Crypto Adoption</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        Crypto remains one of the fastest-growing payment methods for Canadian players due to:\n      </p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li>Faster withdrawals (5\u201320 minutes for BTC/ETH/USDT in TCS tests).</li>\n        <li>Higher limits for high-volume players.</li>\n        <li>Reduced friction during verification.</li>\n        <li>Lower failure rates than bank-linked methods during peak hours.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p>\n        The primary trend in 2025 is the expansion of <strong>USDT-TRC20</strong> as the most commonly offered\n        crypto rail due to low fees and stable transfer times.\n      </p>\n\n      <h3>2.4 Card Payments \u2014 Stable but Slower</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        Visa and Mastercard remain widely supported for deposits but are less reliable for withdrawals due to\n        bank-side restrictions. Processing times remain significantly slower than Interac or crypto.\n      </p>\n\n      <!-- SECTION: BONUS ECONOMICS -->\n      <h2 style=\"margin-top:42px;\">3. Bonus Trends in the Canadian Market (2025)</h2>\n\n      <p>\n        Canadian GEOs exhibit well-defined bonus patterns that differ from global markets.\n        TCS audits across 110+ operators showed that bonus segmentation is increasingly provincial, demographic\n        and payment-method driven.\n      </p>\n\n      <h3>3.1 Welcome Bonus Structures</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        The most stable pattern across Canada in 2024\u20132025 is the <strong>tiered deposit match</strong> structure:\n      </p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li>First deposit: 100% to 200% match</li>\n        <li>Second / third deposit: 25%\u2013100% matches</li>\n        <li>Free spins: 50\u2013200 spins allocated across popular high-RTP slots</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p>\n        Ontario-regulated operators must follow stricter promotional communication rules and offer less aggressive\n        match percentages. Grey-market operators offer larger bonuses but higher wagering.\n      </p>\n\n      <h3>3.2 No-Deposit Bonuses</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        Canada remains one of the strongest regions globally for legitimate no-deposit bonuses.\n        Typical structures:\n      </p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li>20\u201350 free spins</li>\n        <li>C$5\u2013C$20 bonus credits</li>\n        <li>35x\u201360x wagering on spin winnings</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p>\n        Ontario-licensed operators cannot offer public no-deposit bonuses due to promotional restrictions.\n        These offers are entirely a non-Ontario phenomenon.\n      </p>\n\n      <h3>3.3 Real Value Trends</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        The three best proxies for bonus \u201creal value\u201d identified in TCS testing:\n      </p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li><strong>Wagering between 30x\u201340x</strong> on matched deposits.</li>\n        <li><strong>100% slot contribution</strong> with no restricted list beyond high-volatility titles.</li>\n        <li><strong>No max-cashout rules</strong> on standard bonuses.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p>\n        Bonuses with unusually high value (250%+, 300+ free spins) commonly exhibit hidden max-cashout caps\n        or inflated wagering on specific games \u2014 a persistent grey-market pattern.\n      </p>\n\n      <!-- SECTION: PLAYER BEHAVIOUR -->\n      <h2 style=\"margin-top:42px;\">4. Player Behaviour Trends Across Canada</h2>\n\n      <p>\n        TCS behavioural modelling shows clear patterns emerging in the Canadian market, driven by payment convenience,\n        device usage, game preferences and regulatory psychology.\n      </p>\n\n      <h3>4.1 Device and Session Behaviour</h3>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li><strong>Mobile accounts for 72\u201378% of casino sessions</strong> (Android slightly higher than iOS).</li>\n        <li>Average session length: 11\u201317 minutes.</li>\n        <li>Most players consume promotions on mobile but complete withdrawals on desktop.</li>\n        <li>Live dealer games see longer sessions but lower session counts.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <h3>4.2 Provincial Player Profiles</h3>\n\n      <p><strong>Ontario:</strong> Highly brand-aware, bonus-sensitive in a regulated climate, strong loyalty to licensed operators.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>British Columbia:</strong> Strongest adoption of crypto among all provinces, heavy live-dealer usage.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>Quebec:</strong> Higher demand for French-language support, increased interest in game providers popular in France.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>Alberta:</strong> High involvement from high-stakes players, favouring fast-payout operators.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>Atlantic Canada:</strong> Smaller population but high bonus utilisation and longer session durations.</p>\n\n      <h3>4.3 Key Motivations and Friction Points</h3>\n\n      <p><strong>Motivations:</strong></p>\n      <ul>\n        <li>Fast Interac cashouts</li>\n        <li>High-RTP slots and transparent paytables</li>\n        <li>Easy-to-clear wagering</li>\n        <li>Brand reputation and community word-of-mouth</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p><strong>Friction points:</strong></p>\n      <ul>\n        <li>KYC delays due to inconsistent documentation standards</li>\n        <li>Interac velocity limits during peak hours</li>\n        <li>Operators with slow weekday payout windows</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <!-- SECTION: GREY MARKET RISKS -->\n      <h2 style=\"margin-top:42px;\">5. Grey-Market Risks & Enforcement Signals</h2>\n\n      <p>\n        While Canada\u2019s grey-market is stable and longstanding, 2024\u20132025 saw increased enforcement pressures\n        and changes in offshore licensing quality.\n      </p>\n\n      <h3>5.1 Cloned and Imposter Casino Sites</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        Clone sites continue to be one of the biggest threats to Canadian players.\n        These sites copy the branding of legitimate casinos but redirect deposits to untraceable wallets.\n      </p>\n\n      <p><strong>Common indicators:</strong></p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li>URLs containing appended characters (e.g. \u201c.co-casino-ca.net\u201d).</li>\n        <li>No verifiable licence or clickable badge.</li>\n        <li>Redirect chains of 3\u201310 domains during signup.</li>\n        <li>Crypto-only deposit requests sent via chat.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <h3>5.2 Enforcement Against Payment Processors</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        Some Interac and card processors face increased scrutiny due to anti-money laundering pressures.\n        This has led to:\n      </p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li>More identity verification prompts.</li>\n        <li>Inconsistent availability during peak traffic.</li>\n        <li>Operator-to-operator differences in processor reliability.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <h3>5.3 Offshore Licensing Divergence</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        Cura\u00e7ao and Anjouan both underwent structural reform, raising their auditing and operator-vetting standards.\n        This benefits Canadian players indirectly, as operators must maintain higher compliance baselines.\n      </p>\n\n      <!-- SECTION: TCS SCORE INSIGHTS -->\n      <h2 style=\"margin-top:42px;\">6. TCS Score Findings for the Canadian Market (2025)</h2>\n\n      <p>\n        Over 110 operators serving Canada were evaluated under the TCS framework between Q1 2024 and Q1 2025.\n        The Canadian market exhibits scoring patterns that differ from the UK and European ecosystems.\n      </p>\n\n      <h3>6.1 Payout Speed Benchmarks</h3>\n\n      <p><strong>Top-tier operators:</strong></p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li>Interac withdrawals averaging 30 minutes to 2 hours.</li>\n        <li>Crypto withdrawals averaging 6\u201315 minutes.</li>\n        <li>Document verification completed within 12\u201324 hours.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p><strong>Mid-tier operators:</strong></p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li>Interac withdrawals: 4\u201312 hours.</li>\n        <li>Crypto: 20\u201345 minutes.</li>\n        <li>KYC: inconsistent; often 24\u201348 hours.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p><strong>Low-tier operators:</strong></p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li>Interac payouts delayed 24\u201372 hours.</li>\n        <li>Crypto dependent on manual approval.</li>\n        <li>Repeated KYC requests (verification loops).</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <h3>6.2 Bonus Fairness Signals</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        Operators scoring highest in bonus fairness offered:\n      </p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li>Clear, unambiguous wagering details.</li>\n        <li>Immediate bonus activation without manual triggers.</li>\n        <li>No max-cashout limits on matched deposits.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p>\n        Lower-scoring brands consistently used vague or hidden terms, especially for high-multiplier bonus offers.\n      </p>\n\n      <h3>6.3 Licensing Integrity</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        Kahnaw\u00e0ke, Cura\u00e7ao (post-2023 reforms) and Anjouan (post-2024 revisions) licences yield the highest stability\n        in Canadian GEO testing.  \n        Weak licensing or unverifiable operators consistently scored lowest.\n      </p>\n\n      <h3>6.4 Customer Support Honesty</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        Mystery-shopper tests revealed three recurring patterns:\n      </p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li>Operators with transparent payout explanations score significantly higher.</li>\n        <li>Evasive support behaviour is strongly correlated with delayed withdrawals.</li>\n        <li>Support agents who confirm Interac timelines accurately also match real-world payout behaviour.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <h3>6.5 Mobile Optimization</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        More than 70% of Canadian sessions occur on mobile devices; top-ranking operators demonstrated:\n      </p>\n\n      <ul>\n        <li>Instant game launch with minimal server lag.</li>\n        <li>Optimised banking flows for mobile Interac and crypto.</li>\n        <li>Clear, tap-friendly navigation and responsive design.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"tcs-review-block\" style=\"margin-top:38px; padding:26px 28px; border-radius:14px; border:1px solid #3b348f; background:rgba(12,10,46,0.9);\">\n  <span class=\"tcs-label-pill\">For Players \u2022 Practical Impact</span>\n  <h3 style=\"margin-top:10px;\">What This Means for Canadian Players in 2025</h3>\n\n  <p>\n    The trends outlined in this report have direct, real-world implications for how Canadians deposit, withdraw, choose bonuses, manage risk, and avoid unsafe operators. Based on TCS Score audits, banking flow tests, licensing analysis and player-behaviour modelling, here\u2019s what Canadians should expect throughout 2025:\n  </p>\n\n  <ul style=\"margin-top:12px;\">\n\n    <li><strong>Earlier and stricter ID verification across all provinces:</strong>  \n      Both regulated Ontario operators and reputable grey-market casinos outside Ontario are increasing KYC friction.  \n      Expect verification <em>before</em> your first withdrawal and more precise checks for Interac and crypto users.\n    </li>\n\n    <li><strong>Fast Interac cashouts will become the defining quality metric:</strong>  \n      Top-tier casinos now process Interac withdrawals in as little as 30 minutes.  \n      Anything consistently above 6\u201312 hours is a warning sign of processor problems or liquidity issues.\n    </li>\n\n    <li><strong>Crypto will become the most reliable fallback method:</strong>  \n      Banking limits, velocity controls and failed Interac transfers \u2014 especially on weekends \u2014 are pushing players toward BTC and USDT-TRC20.  \n      Crypto payouts remain the fastest, most consistent rail nationwide.\n    </li>\n\n    <li><strong>Bonus structures will tighten, but value is improving:</strong>  \n      Canadian bonuses now favour lower wagering (30x\u201340x), higher RTP slots, and fewer restricted games.  \n      Oversized offers with 250%+ matches or hundreds of spins usually hide predatory terms \u2014 expect more visible transparency from reputable brands.\n    </li>\n\n    <li><strong>Ontario vs. Rest-of-Canada will feel even more different:</strong>  \n      Ontario players get safer oversight but smaller bonuses and stricter promos.  \n      Non-Ontario players will continue seeing significantly larger offers but must rely more heavily on licensing and payout testing to avoid low-quality operators.\n    </li>\n\n    <li><strong>Cloned Canadian casino sites will increase in frequency:</strong>  \n      Scam domains targeting Interac and crypto users are growing.  \n      URL inspection, licence verification and TCS-verified operator lists will matter more than ever.\n    </li>\n\n    <li><strong>Payment processors will add more fraud controls:</strong>  \n      Interac intermediaries have tightened limits, which may slow high-volume or late-night cashouts.  \n      Players should expect more \u201cdeposit verification\u201d and periodic identity prompts across 2025.\n    </li>\n\n    <li><strong>Mobile-first casinos will dominate player satisfaction:</strong>  \n      With 72\u201378% of Canadian sessions now on mobile, gambling sites with poor mobile UI, slow loading or clunky banking will fall behind quickly.  \n      High-performing mobile UX now directly correlates with higher TCS Scores.\n    </li>\n\n  </ul>\n\n  <p style=\"margin-top:14px; opacity:0.88;\">\n    Bottom line: Canadian players can absolutely play safely in 2025 \u2014 but only by choosing well-licensed operators,\n    verifying domains, relying on Interac or trusted crypto rails, and favouring casinos that pass real-world payout,\n    fairness and support audits.\n  </p>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<section class=\"tcs-section tcs-section--deep-navy\" style=\"margin-top:48px;\">\n  <div class=\"tcs-container\">\n    <div class=\"tcs-review-block\">\n\n      <span class=\"tcs-label-pill\">Canada \u2022 Next Steps</span>\n      <h2>Explore More Canadian Casino Insights & Guides</h2>\n\n      <p>\n        This market report is one part of our broader coverage of <strong>Canadian online casinos</strong>.  \n        Use the links below to return to the main Canada hub, compare payout-tested casinos, \n        and explore data-driven guides covering bonuses, payments, safety and provincial regulations.\n      </p>\n\n      <div class=\"tcs-hero-ctas\"\n           style=\"margin-top:20px; display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:16px;\">\n\n        <!-- Cluster Home -->\n        <a href=\"/canada/\" class=\"tcs-btn-primary\">\n          \u2190 Back to Canada Casino Hub\n        </a>\n\n        <!-- Insider / Reports Hub -->\n        <a href=\"/insider-articles/\" class=\"tcs-btn-secondary\">\n          Casino Market Reports & Insider Articles\n        </a>\n\n        <!-- Core CA Guides -->\n        <a href=\"/canada-online-casinos/\" class=\"tcs-btn-secondary\">\n          Best Canadian Online Casinos\n        </a>\n\n        <a href=\"/canada-casino-bonus/\" class=\"tcs-btn-secondary\">\n          Canadian Casino Bonus Guide\n        </a>\n\n        <a href=\"/canada-banking-guide/\" class=\"tcs-btn-secondary\">\n          Canada Banking & Interac Guide\n        </a>\n\n        <!-- Methodology / Trust -->\n        <a href=\"/how-we-rate/\" class=\"tcs-btn-secondary\">\n          How We Rate Online Casinos\n        </a>\n\n      </div>\n\n      <p class=\"tcs-tagline\" style=\"margin-top:22px;\">\n        Use these guides for updated payout testing, bonus analysis, safety insights, \n        and clearer context on how the Canadian online casino market is evolving in 2025.\n      </p>\n\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>";
